{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502257"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:41:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:41:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.33,0.08,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1839"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11707"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45070"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has a medical history of myocardial infarction 12 months ago requiring coronary artery stent placement. Her regular medications include perindopril, metformin, aspirin and clopidogrel. She has been having regular two-yearly screening mammograms since age 55 with no abnormal findings. She has no personal or family history of breast cancer. She asks if she needs to continue with mammographic screening as she finds the procedure uncomfortable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Breast examination reveals no visible or palpable abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding breast cancer screening?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current screening until age 80","Change to screening breast ultrasound","Encourage regular breast awareness","Change to five-yearly mammographic screening","Discontinue all breast cancer screening"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case addresses breast cancer screening in older women. The Australian breast cancer screening program BreastScreen actively invites women aged 50-74 years for free two-yearly mammograms. While women over 74 can continue screening if they choose, they are no longer sent invitations as the benefits become less clear with advancing age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncourage regular breast awareness\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as it empowers women to be familiar with their normal breast. The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners (RACGP) does not recommend routine teaching of breast self-examination (BSE) for asymptomatic women at average risk of breast cancer. This stance is based on evidence indicating that BSE does not significantly reduce mortality rates and may lead to potential harms such as unnecessary biopsies and anxiety due to false-positive results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInstead, the RACGP emphasises the importance of breast awareness. This approach encourages women to become familiar with the normal look and feel of their breasts, enabling them to notice any unusual changes promptly. Women are advised to report any new or concerning changes\u2014such as lumps, nipple alterations, discharge, or skin texture changes\u2014to their general practitioner without delay. While not as effective as mammography for screening, breast awareness is a reasonable ongoing strategy for this age group as it carries no risks or discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current screening until age 80\u003C/strong\u003E is not supported by evidence. The benefits of mammographic screening decrease with age while the harms (false positives, overdiagnosis, discomfort) remain constant. Given this patient\u0027s cardiovascular comorbidities and lack of enthusiasm for continuing, screening mammography is unlikely to provide meaningful benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to screening breast ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as ultrasound is not recommended as a primary screening tool. It is mainly used as a supplemental test in women with dense breasts or to investigate specific abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to five-yearly mammographic screening\u003C/strong\u003E has no evidence base. The recommended interval for mammographic screening is two years based on the natural history of breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinue all breast cancer screening\u003C/strong\u003E is too absolute. While stopping mammography is reasonable, maintaining breast awareness allows for early detection of obvious changes while avoiding the downsides of formal screening.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Breast cancer screening with mammography is recommended for women aged 50-74 years in Australia.","After age 74, women may continue screening if they choose, but are no longer actively invited.","The benefits of screening mammography decrease with age while the harms remain constant."],"references":["Warner E. Clinical practice. Breast-cancer screening. N Engl J Med. 2011;365(11):1025-1032. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1101540","RACGP. Breast cancer: Preventive activities in general practice. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/breast-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70621"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-20T20:20:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T15:00:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1839"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the